attributes.magic: ELF 32-bit LSB executable, Intel 80386, version 1 (SYSV), statically linked, stripped

threat_severity.level_description: Severity MEDIUM because it was considered trojan.

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: This ELF binary is a DDoS botnet agent, likely a variant of the Mirai or Gafgyt/Bashlite families. It exhibits several characteristic malicious behaviors: 1) Anti-analysis/Anti-VM checks by querying '/sys/class/dmi/id/product_name' for 'VMware'. 2) Process killing functionality where it iterates through '/proc', identifies competing malware or system tools (e.g., sshd, wget, curl, and other bots based on hex-string names), and terminates them using SIGKILL. 3) Network attack capabilities including templates for SYN, ACK, HTTP, ICMP, GRE, and UDP floods, evidenced by command strings like '!syn', '!http', and '!udpcustom'. 4) Evasion and persistence mechanisms such as self-daemonization by redirecting standard I/O to '/dev/null' and using a lock file '/tmp/.bot_lock'. 5) String obfuscation using a 32-character hex key ('fd00e82a0a3d86af73deacaa9df16432') to decode internal paths and command-and-control (C2) data.
